### CHAPTER LX.

1\. The sage asked the spirit of wisdom (2) thus: 'Of mankind which are
more conversant with good and evil?'

3\. The spirit of wisdom answered (4) thus: 'Of mankind *he* whose
sojourn <span id="fr_576"></span>[3](#fn_568.md) and business are with the
bad <span id="fr_577"></span>[4](#fn_569.md), and they provide him a name
for good repute and goodness, is the man more conversant with good. 5.
And he whose sojourn and business are with the good <span
id="fr_578"></span>[5](#fn_570.md), and they provide him a name for
disrepute, is the man more conversant with evil.

6\. 'Because it is said, (7, 8) that whoever joins with the good brings
good with *him*, and whoever

<span id="page_107">p. 107</span>

joins with the bad *brings* <span id="fr_579"></span>[1](#fn_571.md)
evil—(9) just like the wind which, when it impinges on stench, is <span
id="fr_580"></span>[2](#fn_572) stench, (10.md) and when it impinges on
perfume, is perfume,—(11) *it* is, therefore, notorious <span
id="fr_581"></span>[3](#fn_573), (12.md) that he whose business is with the
good receives good, (13) and *he* whose business is with the bad
*receives* <span id="fr_582"></span>[4](#fn_574) evil; (14.md) but, even
then, both are to be considered as an experiment (aû*z*mâyi*s*nŏ) <span
id="fr_583"></span>[5](#fn_575.md).'

