### Footnotes

<span id="fn_568"></span>[106:3](sbe24066.htm#fr_576.md) Reading ni*s*astŏ.
L19 has 'whose business is most (vê*s*-ast),' both here and in § 5.

<span id="fn_569"></span>[106:4](sbe24066.htm#fr_577.md) L19 has 'the
good.'

<span id="fn_570"></span>[106:5](sbe24066.htm#fr_578.md) L19 has 'the bad.'

<span id="fn_571"></span>[107:1](sbe24066.htm#fr_579.md) L19 has 'will
bring with *him*' in both clauses, but the repetition is unnecessary in
Pahlavi.

<span id="fn_572"></span>[107:2](sbe24066.htm#fr_580.md) L19 has 'will
bring with *it*,' both here and in § 10.

<span id="fn_573"></span>[107:3](sbe24066.htm#fr_581.md) L19 has 'proper to
know.'

<span id="fn_574"></span>[107:4](sbe24066.htm#fr_582.md) K43 does not
repeat this verb.

<span id="fn_575"></span>[107:5](sbe24066.htm#fr_583.md) L19 has 'by the
result (a*nz*âme*s*n).' The meaning is that, though a man's character is
generally in accordance with the company he keeps, this must not be
assumed without proof; and when the contrary is the case, as stated in
§§ 4, 5, his own disposition must be of a very decided nature. Nêryôsang
seems to have misunderstood the author's argument, and, supposing §§
6-13 to contain a mere illustration of §§ 4, 5, he considered it
necessary to transpose 'the bad' and 'the good' in §§ 4, 5, so as to
make the illustration applicable.

